&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Hello,
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; My refactoring of JNeat has brought me to the speciation code, and
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; I&#39;m finding it tricky to reconcile the JNeat speciation code with
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; descriptions in NEAT papers and discussion in this forum.  There is
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; a lot going on here, but I think I can state the problem simply
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; without getting into the details of the JNeat code.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Ken&#39;s paper describes speciation as occuring every generation.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Speciation entails iterating over the population, and performing
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; some rudimentary clustering using a compatibility function and
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; threshhold.  Pretty straightforward.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Indeed, this algorithm is implemented in JNeat as the speciate()
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; method, but its only invoked at the beginning of evolution and
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; never again!  The growth and death of species afterwards is
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; determined by some code in the epoch() method that does not appear
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; to resemble NEAT speciation.  I&#39;m concerned that whatever JNeat is
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; doing, it isn&#39;t what Ken had in mind, and it leads to some strange
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; behavior.  Attached is a graph showing how the number of species
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; grows during a run of the XOR experiment.  With a population size
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; of 500, it increases almost monotonically to 400 before leveling
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; off after 40 generations.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Shouldn&#39;t the speciate() method be called after ever generation/
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; epoch?  Isn&#39;t this way too many species?  Approximately how many
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; species would you expect for the XOR experiment with 500 individuals?
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Regards,
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Daniel
